# Expert Profile: Tommy Clark (Compound Content Studio)

**Core Thesis:** Ruthless focus on **Middle-of-Funnel (MOFU)** content to avoid the "Broad Reach vs. Aggressive Pitch" trap.

---

## 1. The Strategy: MOFU Dominance
Most LinkedIn content fails by being either too broad (TOFU memes) or too aggressive (BOFU pitches). Clark advocates for a mix that is **60–70% MOFU**.

* **Objective:** Demonstrate expertise without overt self-promotion.
* **Target:** Sophisticated B2B buyers who value methodology over hype.
* **The "Dog-Fooding" Method:** Documenting the internal use of your own product. This acts as a powerful form of social proof, humanizing the software and revealing the strategic logic behind its development.

---

## 2. The Compound Content Allocation Model

| Funnel Stage | Rec. Percentage | Content Format | Objective |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Top of Funnel (TOFU)** | 10–20% | Personal stories; origin myths | Broad awareness and reach |
| **Middle of Funnel (MOFU)** | 60–70% | Frameworks; case studies; teardowns | Trust and authority building |
| **Bottom of Funnel (BOFU)** | 10–20% | Product clips; demo hooks; hard CTAs | Intent capture and conversion |

---

## 3. Implementation Tactics
* **Signature Frameworks:** Provide step-by-step breakdowns of how you solve specific industry problems.
* **Contrarian Takes:** Share "hot takes" on industry best practices to show you aren't just following the crowd.
* **The Library Effect:** Transform the LinkedIn feed from a broadcast channel into a **Library of Authority**. Each post should compound the audience's understanding of your value proposition.

